Technical Stack Specification Document
Project: Comprehensive Travel Planning Application
Core Language: TypeScript (End-to-End)
Document Version: 1.0

1. Project Overview
A full-suite travel planning application designed to generate end-to-end itineraries. The system handles complex business logic including real-time flight and hotel pricing, geospatial proximity searches, weather-based seasonality recommendations, and automated AI-driven scheduling.

2. Architecture Overview
The platform utilizes a decoupled client-server architecture. The frontend handles UI rendering and state management, while a robust backend orchestrates multiple third-party API aggregations, geospatial database queries, and background queues for real-time price monitoring.

3. Frontend Architecture (Client-Side)
The user interface is optimized for speed, accessibility, and complex data visualization (calendars, maps, itineraries).

Component	Technology	Rationale
Framework	Next.js (React)	Enables Server-Side Rendering (SSR) for fast initial load times and strong SEO for travel-related search queries.
Styling	Tailwind CSS	Utility-first framework for rapid, responsive UI development.
UI Components	shadcn/ui	Provides accessible, highly customizable foundational components (date pickers, sliders, modals) without adding bloat.
State Management	React Query (TanStack)	Handles asynchronous data fetching, automatic caching, and loading states for API-heavy interactions.
4. Backend Architecture (Server-Side)
The backend acts as an orchestrator, processing heavy business logic and managing external API rate limits.

Component	Technology	Rationale
Framework	NestJS (Node.js)	Enforces a scalable, enterprise-grade architecture. Natively supports TypeScript and handles complex routing seamlessly.
ORM	Prisma or Drizzle	Provides strict end-to-end type safety between the database and the application layer, preventing runtime errors.
Job Queue	BullMQ	Essential for background processing, specifically monitoring emergency flight price drops and asynchronous API polling.
5. Data Layer (Database & Caching)
The application requires highly relational data storage and rapid retrieval for frequently searched routes.

Primary Database: PostgreSQL

Extension: PostGIS. Crucial for geospatial querying (e.g., finding hotels within a specific radius of a tourist attraction or calculating distances between waypoints).

In-Memory Store: Redis

Used for caching high-volume, repetitive API responses (e.g., standard flight routes or historical weather data) to reduce third-party API costs and improve response times. Also powers the background job queues.

6. Third-Party Integrations (The Data Engine)
The core value of the application relies on aggregating and processing data from specialized external providers.

Booking & Pricing Services
Flights & Hotels: Amadeus API or Duffel API

Provides real-time flight availability, dynamic pricing, and emergency fare lookups.

Location & Environment Services
Mapping & POIs: Google Places API

Supplies accurate geocodes, operating hours (open/close timings), and user ratings for landscapes and attractions.

Climate & Seasonality: Visual Crossing API or OpenWeatherMap

Fetches historical climate data to cross-reference with user budgets and determine the "perfect season" to travel.

AI & Processing
Planning Engine: Google Gemini API or OpenAI API

Processes the aggregated raw data (flights, weather, places) alongside user constraints (budget, days) to generate a structured, optimized daily itinerary in JSON format.

7. System Data Flow
Input Submission: The user submits travel constraints via the Next.js client.

Request Handling: The NestJS backend receives the payload and checks Redis for cached itineraries matching the exact criteria.

Data Aggregation: If no cache exists, the backend concurrently queries Amadeus (flights/hotels), Google Places (timings), and weather APIs.

AI Orchestration: The raw data and constraints are formatted into a prompt and sent to the LLM to structure the day-by-day plan.

Persistence & Delivery: The backend saves the generated itinerary to PostgreSQL, caches the result in Redis, and serves the finalized plan back to the frontend.